title: The Last Known Survivor Out Of The South Tower On 9/11 | World Trade Center Attack | Ron DiFrancesco
description:
Ron DiFrancesco was a Canadian working on a U.S. immigration work visa in the South Tower of the World Trade Center on 9/11. He was a manager at Euro Brokers' office on the 84th floor.

After witnessing the first plane hit the North Tower, and receiving a concerned phone call from a friend in Canada, Ron decided to begin exiting the South Tower. As Ron headed towards the 84th floor elevators the second plane slammed into his building.

Directly in the impact zone, Ron now began his harrowing journey out of the severely damaged tower. Fifty-four minutes after the plane hit the building, Ron stumbled out of the south tower and into the courtyard. Moments later the South Tower collapsed on itself and Ron.

Interview recorded on November 3, 2023

title: Survivor Top 10 Big Moves that Failed Spectacularly
description:
Survivor's Biggest Moves/Blindsides that failed in spectacular fashion.
All Rights to CBS and Survivor.
Sorry I had to cut the last one for copyright reasons.

List:
#10: Survivor Caramoan: Andrea. With an immunity idol in her pocket, Andrea attempted to blindside her biggest ally, Brenda. Brenda got wind of Andrea's plan and her alliance turned on her, taking her out with her idol.

#9: Survivor Second Chance: Fishbach. The entire game, Fishbach despised Joe and wanted him out. Joe finally didn't win immunity and Fishbach decided to play his secret advantage, which was the first ever steal-a-vote in Survivor. Fishbach stole Joe's vote, voted for Joe but was still blindsided by part of his alliance.

#8: Survivor Gabon: Randy. Randy's allies had been taken out in Marcus and Charlie, and he decided to make camp terrible for everyone else to receive votes, and counting on Bob having the hidden immunity idol. Bob had made a fake idol, and Sugar convinced Bob to give it to Randy, and Randy's plan backfired on him.

#7: Heroes vs Villains: JT. Nobody on Heroes vs Villains had seen Russell play before, and JT was adamant that Russell was good. With a small amount of cross-tribal communication, JT gave Russell his idol to 'save' him from the women on the Villains tribe. JT's idol was then used against him from Parvati to block out Sandra and Jerri's votes, and JT went home.

#6: Survivor 42: Drea. Omar had told Mike about Drea's 'Knowledge is Power' advantage, so Mike gave his idol to someone else to hold on to so Drea couldn't steal it. Drea then used her extra vote to attempt to get out Mike, but she didn't have the numbers to pull off the blindside.

#5: Game Changers: Cirie/Michaela. Sarah had given Cirie her steal-a-vote advantage as a sign of trust, but Cirie used it against Sarah to show her that Tai was being a rat in the game. Cirie couldn't use the advantage herself, and Sarah rallied the numbers to eliminate Michaela; Cirie's closest ally.

#4: David vs Goliath: Gabby. Gabby had done all of her moves with Christian in the game, her closest ally. She then decided to try and take out Christian to make moves of her own to get to the end. Gabby, taking a leap of faith couldn't trust her newfound allies who told Christian about the move, he first didn't believe them but then used his idol to take cancel out his votes, and Gabby was blindsided.

#3: Winners at War: Sandra. Sandra had an idol that could only be used at their next tribal council. Feeling safe, she wanted to make a big move to get out one of the guys, so she gave her idol to Denise. Denise already had a second idol, gave her idol to Jeremy as a sign of trust, and used her idol to take out Sandra.

#2: Micronesia: Erik. Erik continuously won individual immunity as he was the target of the Black Widow Brigade alliance. Feeling guilty about his past votes, the Black Widow Brigade hatched a plan to guilt Erik into giving up immunity and being in their good graces once again.

#1: Second Chance: Kimmi. Feeling on the bottom of her alliance, Kimmi decided to flip and side with Keith and Wentworth in the Final 6. Once Wentworth and Jeremy played their idols, there was another tie between Tasha and Kimmi. The group then had to decide to send Tasha, Kieth or Kimmi home, which lead to her demise. Had she flipped one vote sooner, she may have been in the final 3.


Honorable Mentions:
Survivor: Amazon: Christy
Survivor: Blood vs Water: Katie
Survivor: Worlds Apart: Dan
Survivor: Kaoh Rong: Jenny
Survivor: Millennials vs Gen X: Jessica
Survivor: Game Changers: JT
Survivor: Winners at War: Kim
Survivor: 41: Liana

title: Jeju Air plane crash survivor arrives at hospital in Seoul | ABS-CBN News
description:
STORY: One of two survivors of South Koreaâ€™s Jeju Air crash at Muan International Airport, which killed at least 174 people, was transported to hospital in Seoul on Sunday (December 29).

Jeju Air flight 7C2216, arriving from the Thai capital Bangkok with 175 passengers and six crew on board, was attempting to land shortly after 9 a.m. (0000 GMT) at the airport in the south of the country, South Korea's transport ministry said.

Two people, both crew members, were rescued, and officials have suggested the rest are presumed dead.

It is the deadliest air accident ever on South Korean soil, and the worst involving a South Korean airline in nearly three decades, according to ministry data

title: Exit Interview with Rachel Lamont on Survivor 47
description:
Subscribe Now: http://weknowsurvivor.com

Join host Rob Cesternino as he sits down with Rachel Lamont, the triumphant winner of Survivor 47. Together, they explore the strategic brilliance and pivotal moments that led Rachel to victory. From intense fire-making challenges to unexpected alliances, Rachel shares her journey with candor and excitement.

In this episode, Rachel recounts her experience at the final Tribal Council, where her competition with Sam was fierce. She reveals how winning the final five immunity gave her confidence, yet Sam's performance kept her on edge. Rachel also dives into her decision-making process during the final four fire-making challenge, aiming for a final three of women and the drama that ensued with Sam's fiery win. Reflecting on her gameplay, Rachel discusses the challenges of adapting her strategy, especially when faced with unexpected moves from players like Andy. She also touches on the early game "rice stealing" incident and how it shaped her approach moving forward.

Key Points of Interest:
- Rachel's strategic choice in the final four fire-making challenge
- The impact of the early "rice stealing" incident on her game
- Her innovative use of the shot in the dark play
- The rivalry with Genevieve and its influence on her strategy
- Rachel's idol play at the final six and its significance

title: Exit Interview: Fifth Juror Voted Out Survivor 47
description:
Subscribe Now: http://weknowsurvivor.com

Rob Cesternino sits down with Caroline Vidmar to unpack her unexpected exit from the game. As a recently eliminated contestant, Caroline shares her insights and strategies, offering a behind-the-scenes look at her gameplay. The conversation reveals the complexities of her alliances and the pivotal moments that shaped her journey on the island.

Caroline reflects on her surprise elimination, explaining how she managed to influence votes without drawing attention. She discusses her flexible end-game strategy, highlighting her comfort in aligning with players like Sue, Teeny, Andy, and Sam. Caroline also delves into the final vote that led to her departure, sharing her thoughts on Andy's plan and her own instincts at Tribal Council. Throughout the discussion, Caroline provides a candid look at her perceptions of fellow contestants and her strategic decisions.

Rob and Caroline discuss:
- Caroline's strategic maneuvering to influence votes while staying under the radar
- Her evolving perception of Andy and his emotional gameplay
- The decision to target Kyle over Genevieve and its implications
- Caroline's competitive nature and self-critical approach
- The role of Sue's idol in Caroline's strategic planning

Will Caroline's strategic insights and alliances have a lasting impact on the game? How will her relationships with players like Andy and Sue shape the dynamics moving forward?

title: Exit Interview with Sam Phalen on Survivor 47
description:
Subscribe Now: http://weknowsurvivor.com

Join Rob Cesternino as he sits down with Survivor 47 contestant Sam Phalen for an in-depth look at his journey on the island. This episode offers a unique glimpse into Sam's strategic mind, exploring the highs and lows of his gameplay, including his memorable final tribal council performance and the intricate "Operation Italy" strategy.

Sam reflects on the fire-making challenge, describing it as an "out-of-body experience" where unexpected elements like the wind played a crucial role. He shares insights into his final tribal council, where he anticipated more votes than he received, and discusses the layers of his "Operation Italy" strategy, which involved aligning with bigger threats and using a fake idol to his advantage. Sam also recounts the dramatic tribal council where Rachel's idol play led to Andy's elimination, showcasing his quick thinking and adaptability. Additionally, he reveals a pivotal decision to inform Sol about a secret plan, highlighting the complex dynamics of trust and strategy in the game.

Key Points of Interest:
- Sam's unexpected challenges during the fire-making task
- The strategic depth of "Operation Italy" and its impact
- Rachel's idol play and its consequences for Andy
- Sam's decision to reveal a secret plan to Sol
- Reward challenge picks and their strategic implications

title: South Korea Plane Crash Survivor Arrives At Hospital In Seoul | South Korea Plane Crash | N18G
description:
Jeju Air flight 7C2216, arriving from the Thai capital Bangkok with 175 passengers and six crew on board, was attempting to land shortly after 9 a.m. at the airport in the south of the country, South Korea's transport ministry said.

Two people, both crew members, were rescued, and officials have suggested the rest are presumed dead.

It is the deadliest air accident ever on South Korean soil, and the worst involving a South Korean airline in nearly three decades, according to ministry data.

Stranded in the beautiful islands of Fiji, the castaways are forced to adapt to their physical and social surroundings. The mental and physical challenges force players to choose between personal risk and reward, while still navigating the complex social game and attempting to forge alliances to last another day. The individuals competing are from diverse backgrounds with the same ultimate goal: to outwit, outplay, and outlast and ultimately be crowned Sole Survivor. Originating in 2000, the show pioneered a genre that has become a cultural staple as it garnered monumental viewership, starting conventions like confessionals, villains, and manipulated narratives. Emphasizing interpersonal dynamics, paved the way for subsequent reality hits, shaping the genre into a permanent part of American entertainment.
